its weapon.

30:47.079 --> 30:50.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: OK, that got
my attention.

30:50.816 --> 30:53.852 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our science correspondent Miles
O'Brien is
here to spell out some more.

30:53.885 --> 30:56.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: William, I should
have brought
the popcorn.

30:56.221 --> 30:56.822 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

30:56.855 --> 30:58.757 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Exactly.

30:58.790 --> 31:02.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have been to Jupiter before.
NASA's been
there a couple of times. What's
different

31:02.861 --> 31:04.696 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
this time?

31:04.730 --> 31:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, depending
on how you
count, we have had about 10
missions to Jupiter.

31:06.832 --> 31:12.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of them have been flybys,
Voyager, Pioneer
notable among them, New Horizons
as well.

31:12.571 --> 31:18.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We of course had the orbiting
mission of Galileo,
which began in the mid-'90s into
the early

31:18.143 --> 31:22.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
2000s, which did most science
around Jupiter
and its moons.

31:22.380 --> 31:26.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's the big treasure
trove of data.
And all the while, the Hubble
telescope has

31:26.818 --> 31:32.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
captured a lot of interesting
data from Jupiter.
And in particular, back in 1994,
you may recall

31:32.491 --> 31:37.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when the Shoemaker-Levy 9 comet,
that fragment
comet, struck Jupiter, Hubble
got some amazing

31:37.729 --> 31:39.131 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
images of those impacts.

31:39.164 --> 31:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But all off this is skin-deep.

31:41.099 --> 31:43.869 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So what are we
trying to
learn this time?

31:43.902 --> 31:47.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, there's a
lot of things
we can learn from Jupiter.

31:47.839 --> 31:51.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jupiter, of course, is the
biggest plant in
our solar system of eight
planets. It's about

31:51.843 --> 31:56.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
two-and-a-half times the mass of
all the rest
of the solar system combined, of
the planets,

31:56.782 --> 32:04.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is. And it's really like a
big deep freeze
for how our solar system began
four billion

32:04.122 --> 32:05.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
years ago.

32:06.024 --> 32:08.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It really hasn't changed very
much. So scientists
want to understand what's kind
of beneath

32:08.794 --> 32:13.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the surface there, how much
hydrogen, how
much water, what about the
magnetic field,

32:13.799 --> 32:18.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what about the gravitational
pull, is there
a solid core? All these are
important clues

32:18.837 --> 32:24.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and information for us to
understand how our
solar system progressed, how it
developed

32:24.442 --> 32:28.647 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and really how we came to be
where we are
today.

32:28.680 --> 32:32.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The principal investigator of
the mission
is Scott Bolton, and he fills us
in on some

32:32.818 --> 32:34.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the big questions.

32:34.719 --> 32:38.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT BOLTON, NASA: The major
science objectives
of Juno are, one, to understand
how Jupiter

32:38.323 --> 32:44.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
formed and what is it made out
of. We want
the recipe of solar systems, and
we are at

32:44.229 --> 32:46.331 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the ingredient list level.

32:46.364 --> 32:51.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So we're gathering the
ingredient list and
understanding how Jupiter is
structured. So

32:51.837 --> 32:56.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the most important objectives
are understanding
Jupiter's formation and how that
relates to

32:56.975 --> 32:59.010 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the formation of other planets,
including
us

32:59.044 --> 33:03.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, if Juno
isn't landing
on Jupiter, how is it going to
see beneath

33:03.415 --> 33:05.250 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the surface?

33:05.283 --> 33:07.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's not so easy,
is it? You're
talking about, first of all, a
very hazardous

33:07.853 --> 33:09.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
place to do business, if you
will.

33:09.988 --> 33:14.960 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the key is, they to
