meaning.

44:00.004 --> 44:05.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the recent BookExpo America
in Chicago,
Jeffrey Brown talked to
journalist and author

44:05.142 --> 44:10.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sebastian Junger. His new book
is "Tribe:
On Homecoming and Belonging."

44:10.548 --> 44:13.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Start with the
definition.
What do you mean by tribe?

44:13.784 --> 44:16.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER, Author,
"Tribe: On Homecoming
and Belonging": The real an
ancient meaning

44:16.287 --> 44:21.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of tribe is the community that
you live in
that you share resources with
that you would

44:21.959 --> 44:23.728 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
risk your life to defend.

44:23.761 --> 44:29.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, that's the real meaning
of tribe.
Of course, in modern society,
that structure,

44:29.166 --> 44:33.404 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that tribal structure has been
lost. That
loss of tribe also costs people
psychologically.

44:33.437 --> 44:38.776 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Did this grow
specifically
out of your work as a war
reporter or...

44:38.809 --> 44:41.913 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Well, there
was this puzzling
thing that I noticed.

44:41.946 --> 44:45.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of the soldiers that I was
with -- and
I was at a remote outpost called
Restrepo.

44:45.850 --> 44:47.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

44:47.718 --> 44:50.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: It was a
20-man position,
everyone sleeping basically
shoulder to shoulder

44:50.121 --> 44:52.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the dirt at first and then in
these little
hooches.

44:52.957 --> 44:59.196 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it was very intimate, very
close, very
connected, emotionally connected
experience.

44:59.230 --> 45:03.167 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And after the deployment, which
was -- the
deployment was hellish. And
afterward the

45:03.200 --> 45:09.540 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
deployment, a lot of those guys
missed the
combat and they didn't want to
come home to

45:09.574 --> 45:11.342 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
America.

45:11.375 --> 45:14.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is it about modern society
that's so
repellent even to people that
are from there?

45:14.979 --> 45:17.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my book "Tribe" is an
attempt to answer
that question.

45:17.548 --> 45:22.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, tribe can be
any kind of
community? Does it have to be a
certain size?

45:22.687 --> 45:26.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Does it have to be -- how
organized does it
have to be?

45:26.057 --> 45:32.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Well, humans
lose the ability
to connect emotionally with
people after a

45:32.263 --> 45:34.465 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
certain number, right at 150.

45:34.498 --> 45:39.737 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there is a limit to the
number of people
we can connect with and that we
can feel capable

45:39.770 --> 45:42.106 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of sacrificing ourselves for if
need be.

45:42.139 --> 45:47.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What happens,
though, when
you're a member of a larger
corporation, a

45:47.912 --> 45:50.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
larger town, a larger -- a
religious group?

45:50.114 --> 45:54.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I think the
reason those
things feel good is because they
come close

45:54.952 --> 46:00.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
enough to replicating the
connections of tribe
that it's sort of familiar in
human terms.

46:00.257 --> 46:07.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're not tribes. Tribes,
really, you have
to live with the people in your
tribe for

46:07.732 --> 46:13.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it to be a tribe in the sort of
ancient sense.
Now, what happens when society
experiences

46:13.170 --> 46:16.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a collapse, like the Blitz in
London or an
earthquake or something like
that, is that

46:16.540 --> 46:21.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people are forced into communal
situations
with each other in order to
survive.

46:21.646 --> 46:25.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So you're looking
at our society
and seeing an affluence and
seeing -- but

46:25.950 --> 46:27.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
seeing a kind of a
disconnection?

46:27.752 --> 46:31.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Well, the
irony of modern
society, for all of its very
real benefits

46:31.789 --> 46:37.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- I mean, modern society is a
miracle in
a lot of ways, right? But as
affluence goes

46:37.862 --> 46:41.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up in a society, the suicide
rate tends to
go up, not down.

46:41.899 --> 46:52.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As affluence goes up in a
society, the depression
rate goes up. When a crisis
hits, then people's

46:52.043 --> 46:56.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
psychological health starts to
improve. After
9/11 in New York City -- I live
in New York

46:56.580 --> 47:02.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- and after 9/11, the suicide
rate went down
in New York, not up. It went
down. It improved.

47:02.820 --> 47:08.025 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Violent crime went down. Murder
went down.
There was a sense of everyone
needs each other.

47:08.059 --> 47:13.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once you're called to serve
your community,
in some way, you sort of forget
your own problems.

47:13.798 --> 47:20.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What's your sense
of how technology
changes -- the Internet? Much
discussion about

47:20.204 --> 47:24.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the communities that can form,
small communities
that can form on the Internet.
In some ways,

47:24.809 --> 47:28.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we lose a sense of a larger
community, but
we have these niche communities.

47:28.179 --> 47:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I don't talk
about the Internet
in my book.

47:31.315 --> 47:33.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

47:33.150 --> 47:38.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: But they are
communities
only in the most abstract and
unhuman sense.

47:38.756 --> 47:40.324 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So that's not
enough?

47:40.357 --> 47:42.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: It's not
enough.

47:42.126 --> 47:45.730 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, actually, I would say the
Internet is
doubly dangerous for all -- and,
again, for

47:45.763 --> 47:52.636 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all of its miraculous capacity,
not only does
it not provide real community
and real human

47:52.670 --> 47:57.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
connection. It gives you the
illusion that
it does, right?

47:57.742 --> 48:05.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, oh, I have got lots of
friends on Facebook,
so I'm good. You're actually not
good. And

48:05.816 --> 48:10.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not an expert in this, but
from what I
studied for my book "Tribe,"
what you need

48:11.021 --> 48:14.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is to feel people, smell them,
hear them,
feel them around you.

48:14.925 --> 48:18.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I mean, that's the human
connection that we
evolved for, for hundreds of
thousands of

48:18.729 --> 48:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
years. The Internet doesn't
provide that.

48:21.999 --> 48:25.202 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We talk about
things having
broken down in Washington.

48:25.236 --> 48:26.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Right.

48:26.504 --> 48:28.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: And we're
watching a political
campaign. Right?

48:28.038 --> 48:28.973 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Right.

48:29.006 --> 48:30.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Very much us
against them.

48:30.775 --> 48:32.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Right.

48:32.643 --> 48:37.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Does the notion
of tribes allow
us to have a cohesion that we
also think we

48:37.481 --> 48:38.449 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
need as a country?

48:38.482 --> 48:40.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yes, it's a
great question.

48:40.918 --> 48:45.389 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think what you're seeing in
this political
season are political camps
deciding that they

48:45.422 --> 48:52.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are their own tribe and it's us
against them.
And I think the trick -- and
this country

48:52.363 --> 48:58.602 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is in a very, very tricky place
socially,
economically, politically -- I
think the trick,

48:58.636 --> 49:03.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you want to be a functioning
country, a
nation, a viable nation, you
have to define

49:04.008 --> 49:09.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tribe to include the entire
country, even
people you disagree with.

49:09.180 --> 49:12.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Disagreement is great, debate is
great, conflict
is great. It's how we all get
better.

49:12.716 --> 49:14.418 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

49:14.451 --> 49:18.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: What you can't
do is have
contempt for your fellow
citizens. That is

49:18.589 --> 49:20.424 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
destructive.

49:20.457 --> 49:24.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No soldier in a trench in a
platoon in combat
would have contempt for their
trench mate.

49:24.595 --> 49:29.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They might not like them. They
disagree with
them, but you don't have
contempt for someone

49:29.400 --> 49:34.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that your life depends on. And
that's what
we're falling into in the
political dialogue

49:34.071 --> 49:38.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in this country. And in my
opinion, that is
more dangerous to this country
than ISIS is,

49:38.542 --> 49:41.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean literally like more of a
threat to
our nation.

49:41.078 --> 49:44.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But as the tribe
increases,
the hard -- cohesion gets
harder, right?

49:44.348 --> 49:45.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Absolutely.

49:46.016 --> 49:48.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, no one is saying this is
going to
be easy, but you do have -- to
understand

49:48.752 --> 49:53.424 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the task, you have to understand
your origins.
You have to understand why
humans are the

49:53.457 --> 49:56.861 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way we are and what the cost of
modern society
has been.

49:56.894 --> 50:00.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once you understand -- and
that's what my
book tries to explain. Once you
understand

50:00.531 --> 50:07.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, it's going to be much
easier to devise,
to jerry-rig a new solution to a
new problem.

50:07.471 --> 50:13.344 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, did all this
make you think
which tribes you belong to or
your own tribe?

50:13.377 --> 50:18.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I mean, sadly,
I grew up
in the -- in the loneliest place
in the world,

50:18.349 --> 50:20.117 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
an American suburb.

50:20.150 --> 50:24.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like, I wish I had a tribe. We
don't. We just
don't. That's the problem.
That's why our

50:24.321 --> 50:29.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
depression rate, our suicide
rate, all that
stuff is through the roof.
That's the tragedy

50:29.460 --> 50:30.628 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of modern society.

50:30.661 --> 50:33.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Short of a Blitz
or short of
a 9/11...

50:33.664 --> 50:35.599 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Right, the
apocalypse, right.

50:35.633 --> 50:39.003 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, what do
people do in their
daily life to find that?

50:39.036 --> 50:44.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Well, I think
if you try
to -- if you imagine your life
in terms of

50:44.108 --> 50:49.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the community you live in, and
you try to
connect personally to the people
in your community,

50:49.647 --> 50:54.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
even though you drive 40 miles
away to go
to work, I think that's
enormously beneficial

50:54.351 --> 50:55.886 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and therapeutic.

50:55.920 --> 50:59.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, the
book is "Tribe:
On Homecoming and Belonging."

50:59.390 --> 51:00.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sebastian Junger, thank you very
much.

